**glm-ocr's turn-ending token isn't registered as an end-of-generation token under llama-server, so the model keeps decoding past the end of its answer and transcribes the page a second time.**

The model has two EOS ids (`<|endoftext|>` = 59246 and `<|user|>` = 59253), and like the rest of the GLM-4 family it normally closes an answer by emitting `<|user|>`. I range-fetched the header of the actual registry blob and confirmed it records both ids **only** in Ollama's own `tokenizer.ggml.eos_token_ids` array, with no `tokenizer.ggml.eot_token_id`. Since the switch to llama-server for GGML models, that file is loaded through `llama/compat` — and llama.cpp never reads `eos_token_ids`; it builds its EOG set from the singular `eos`/`eot`/`eom` keys plus a hard-coded list of token names that doesn't include `<|user|>`. So when the model ends its turn, llama-server treats it as an ordinary token, the context now reads as a fresh user turn with the same image attached, and the model OCRs the page again. That's the duplicated table, the stray ``` fences and the long runtime in the report. The identical mechanism explains #16892, where even `hi` runs away.

The fix is in `handle_glmocr()` in `llama/compat/llama-ollama-compat.cpp`: when a legacy `glmocr` GGUF has no `eot_token_id`, look `<|user|>` up in the vocab and publish it as EOT, which llama.cpp does treat as EOG. This mirrors what `convert/convert_glmocr.go` already writes for new conversions, and follows the existing precedent in that file (`handle_llama3`, `handle_glm4moelite` fix EOG metadata the same way). It's guarded on the key being absent, so newly converted files are untouched.

Verification: I reproduced llama.cpp b9888's EOG rules against the real blob's KVs — before the change the EOG set is just `{<|endoftext|>}`, after it, it also contains `<|user|>`. The compat translation unit compiles cleanly against the pinned llama.cpp, and `go test ./convert/ ./model/renderers/ ./model/parsers/` passes, including a new focused test pinning the same invariant on the conversion path. What I could *not* do is run glm-ocr on the reported image on a GPU, so the end-to-end "no longer repeats" claim rests on the metadata analysis rather than an observed run; NOTES.md says so explicitly, along with the note that `llama/compat` has no test harness in-tree, so the C++ change itself isn't unit-tested.
